Good point on parry. I am often able to work it so I am one-on-one in melee, but if not, there is a penalty to parry and block. (Not toughness or Aug Con, though.) I will have to decide how much the penalty should be. In addition, I need to penalize parry and block because they do not work on magical attacks. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#efe0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kjeld>Kjeld</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Fervent</span><br>  Posts: 128<br> <font color=#ff0000>(10/24/02 12:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=366.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hmm</span><hr size=1> Maybe - I'm not convinced, though. It seems to me that melee's big complaint is that they are hit more than they hit. Hence, the price reduction for purge and ignore pain and the need for melee balance.<br>
-----<br>
<br>
What I mean is &quot;beeing on the receiving end of a melee attack, sucessful or not&quot;. <br>
<br>
The price reduction for purge and IP aim was more about reducing melee vulnerability to magical attack imho.<br>
<br>
I'll try to explain my math a little better.<br>
<br>
Imagine a 8 vs 8 group, with, in both group, 4 melee class and 4 casters. Assuming any enemy meleer will have an equal chance of attacking any opponent, regardless of his class and that there is no 2vs1 battle, you will be attacking someone (caster or melee, regardless) in melee 100% of the time (of course), but there is only 50% chance you'll be attacked by an enemy melee class initally.<br>
<br>
Well, my example is oversimplified , but the fact is melees attack targets are spread between meleers and casters. A melee is still attacking everytime, yet he is not always the victim of another's melee attack.<br>
<br>
----<br>
Mathematically impossible. :P For every person hitting someone in RvR, there is a person being hit.<br>
----<br>
Not accurate : for every melee hitting someone in RvR, there is a melee OR caster being hit<br>
<br>
Remember, parry help you avoid *melee* attack only. *weapon skill* help you hit anyone, melee or magician.<br>
<br>
Parry only work when you are facing the enemy attacking you. Your have a penalty on your parry skill when attacking by multiple opponents. You have a penalty on your parry skill when your opponent use a 2 handed weapon. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c2a2><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=moztli>Moztli</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Participant</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#ff0000>(10/24/02 12:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=366.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hmm</span><hr size=1> I completely concur that parry, blocking, and even the magic resistance boost are situational defenses. That seems to point to toughness (and perhaps Aug Con to some extent) as a source of &quot;universal&quot; defense via increased hit points.(Admittedly more hit points don't reduce mez/stun times, but still they allow you to aborb more damage when you are.) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#efe0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mbolme>mbolme</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Participant</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#ff0000>(10/24/02 11:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=366.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Skald Realm Abilities</span><hr size=1> &gt; What I mean is &quot;beeing on the receiving end of a melee attack, sucessful or not&quot;. <br>
<br>
I think we have come to agreement then. My assumption is that you get 60% of your damage through magic and 40% through melee. This means you are getting hit roughly 1/2 as much as you are hitting. However, you are still taking about a point of damage for every point you dish out.<br>
<br>
Here is my rewritten analysis on parry:<br>
<br>
Analysis<br>
You can parry with a one-handed or two-handed weapon, plus you can spec parrying. If you take 40% of your damage from melee, you need to adjust parry to account for that. However, parry needs to be adjusted further, because the chance to parry is halved against two-handed weapons, divided by the number of opponents attacking you, and is ineffective when meleed from behind. I am going to adjust by 0.67 (say 2/3 melee are two-handed) * .75 (multiple opponent adjustment) = 50%. If you spec parry to 17, then your chance to parry moves from 13% to 16%, and your overall damage is reduced 0.50 (parry adjust) * 0.40 (melee adjust) * (1- .84/.87) = 0.7%.<br>
